{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa05471c-b6c9-4eac-bc6f-f938ba990968","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes without `createdump`, you have two options:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** – macOS automatically generates `.ips` (or `.crash`) files in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain the stack trace, signal info, and thread state.\n\n2. **Core dumps** – Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nFor most NativeAOT crashes, the `.ips` crash report is the quickest path to a stack trace. You can open it in any text editor or Console.app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f4f50a3c-c66b-47cc-b0ef-a95481f492a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"C808:2A1AB:1E885FB:21CAEF8:6A052983"},"id":"cd695e56-54fc-4f6d-86c8-cb570ceb14cb","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:46:50.926Z","parentId":"8b173a9f-0518-405f-ae0c-25fa7105006c"}
